The '''2007 Monte Carlo Rally''' (formally known as the '''{{lang|fr|75<sup>e</sup> Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo}}''') was a [[rallying]] [[autosports]] race held over four days between {{nowrap|18 January}} and {{nowrap|21 January 2007}}, and operated out of {{lang|fr|[[Valence, Dr<U+00F4>me]]}}, France. It was the first race of the [[2007 World Rally Championship season|2007 World Rally Championship (WRC) season]]. Contested over fifteen stages at a length of {{convert|328.54|km|abbr=off}}, [[S<U+00E9>bastien Loeb]] won the race for the [[Citro<U+00EB>n Total World Rally Team]]. [[Dani Sordo]] finished second in the other Citr<U+00F6>en works car, with [[Marcus Gr<U+00F6>nholm]] finishing third in a [[BP-Ford World Rally Team|Ford]].

Loeb, driving an all new [[Citro<U+00EB>n C4 WRC]] car which had been in development throughout 2006, took control of the race from the outset, winning the two stages on the first day and four more stages over the following three days. His teammate Sordo kept the pressure on, winning three stages, but on Stage 6, Loeb extended his lead from 6.6 seconds to nearly 24 seconds, and from thereon became unattainable. Each stage on the first two [[Leg (rallying)|Leg]]s were won by either Loeb or Sordo, and it wasn't until Saturday afternoon on the second run of the day's stages, that other drivers could effectively challenge them. The last two days of the race consisted of a duel between [[Mikko Hirvonen]], who drove a factory 2006 model [[Ford Focus RS WRC]], and [[Chris Atkinson]] in a factory [[Subaru World Rally Team#World Rally Car Impreza GD, 2001<U+2013>2008|Subaru Impreza WRC 2006]]. After Hirvonen completed Stage 2 in fourth place, Atkinson took the position on Stage 3 and held onto it throughout Friday and into Saturday morning's stages. On Stage 12 on Saturday afternoon, Hirvonen retook fourth, Atkinson regained it on Stage 13 but then lost it to Hirvonen again following Stage 14. Atkinson won the final stage on Sunday morning, and finished the race back in fourth position.

Controversially, the 2007 Monte Carlo Rally was no longer based in [[Monaco]] and localities nearby, where it had been held in recent years. The event only visited [[Monte Carlo]] with its final [[special stage (rallying)|special stage]], a short run on part of the [[Circuit de Monaco]] and the rest of the time was spent in and around Valence hundreds of kilometres north of Monaco in the {{lang|fr|[[Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes]]}} region. Many of the locations had not been visited since the 1990s, such as the {{lang|fr|[[Vercors Plateau|Vercors]]}} and {{lang|fr|[[Ard<U+00E8>che]]}}, and only one top level driver had competitively driven on the roads before. The 2007 event also marked the return of the nighttime stages.

Loeb's win was his fourth at Monte Carlo and twenty-ninth in WRC. It was the sixth time that he had achieved a podium position there, which brought his WRC podium finishes to forty-eight. He earned ten points in the [[List of World Rally Championship Drivers' champions|World Rally Championship for Drivers]]. Sordo was two points behind him, while Gr<U+00F6>nholm was in third position with six points. With Atkinson and Hirvonen in fourth and fifth place, [[Petter Solberg]], [[Toni Gardemeister]] and [[Jan Kopeck<U+00FD>]] were the other points finishers. In the [[List of World Rally Championship Constructors' champions|World Rally Championship for Manufacturers]], [[Citro<U+00EB>n Total World Rally Team]] earned the maximum eighteen points for their 1<U+2013>2 finish, [[BP Ford World Rally Team]] placed second, with ten points, with the [[Subaru World Rally Team]] placing third with eight points.

==Report==
===Background===
The 2007 Monte Carlo Rally was the first round of the [[2007 World Rally Championship season|2007 World Rally Championship (WRC) season]] after taking a six-week break since the last race of the [[2006 World Rally Championship season|2006 season]] in [[Great Britain]].<ref name="Pre-event">{{cite press |url=http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Information/WRC/Press_Conferences/2007/mon_conf1.html |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo Pre-event Press Conference |accessdate=14 April 2012 |date=18 January 2007 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> It was held over four days from {{nowrap|Thursday, 18 January}} to {{nowrap|Sunday, 21 January 2007}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fia.com/sport/Championships/WRC/Stage_Maps/2007/Monte_Carlo/stage_map.html |title=2007 Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo |accessdate=16 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> With pressure from the president of {{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Fran<U+00E7>aise du Sport Automobile]]}} and being beset with criticism for running a chaotic route in the [[2006 Monte Carlo Rally]],<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /> {{lang|fr|[[Automobile Club de Monaco]]}} (ACM), the rally organisers, chose to move 2007's race away from Monte Carlo and the roads around {{lang|fr|[[Alpes-Maritimes]]}} and other departments within the {{lang|fr|[[Provence-Alpes-C<U+00F4>te d'Azur]]}} region.<ref name="Yearbook 50" /> Instead, the rally HQ was set up in {{lang|fr|[[Valence, Dr<U+00F4>me]]}},<ref name=Pirelli 44-45">Holmes (2007); pp. 44<U+2013>45.</ref> almost {{convert|400|km|abbr=on}} away from Monte Carlo,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.viamichelin.com/web/Itineraires?&strStartLocid=31NDFzeTAxMGNORE11TnpRd05EYz04Tnk0ME1qVTI=&&strDestLocid=31NDJkdGMxMGNORFF1T1RJNU9ERT1jTkM0NE9EazRPUT09 |title=ViaMichelin directions for Monaco Valence |accessdate=15 April 2012 |publisher=[[Michelin]]}}</ref> with most stages being held in {{lang|fr|[[Ard<U+00E8>che]]}}.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> While some stages were brand new to the rally, some places, such as {{lang|fr|[[Saint-Jean-en-Royans]]}}, {{lang|fr|[[Burzet]]}}, {{lang|fr|[[Saint-Martial, Ard<U+00E8>che|Saint-Martial]]}}, {{lang|fr|[[Lalouvesc]]}}, {{lang|fr|[[Saint-Bonnet-le-Froid]]}}, {{lang|fr|[[Saint-Barth<U+00E9>lemy-Grozon]]}}, and the ''{{lang|fr|[[Saint-Pierreville]]}} <U+2013> {{lang|fr|[[Antraigues-sur-Volane]]}}'' route had played host to Monte Carlo Rally stages in the 1990s and earlier. Only [[Manfred Stohl]], driving for [[OMV-Kronos Citro<U+00EB>n World Rally Team]], was familiar with these roads, as he had competed on them in the late 1990s.<ref>Holmes  (2007); pp. 146, 149.</ref><ref name="Yearbook 50">Bourret, Joubin (2007); p. 50.</ref>

Although the 25,000 spectators seemed pleased that the rally had returned to the region, the drivers, team bosses and [[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA; WRC's governing body) were less enthusiastic.<ref name="Yearbook 51">Bourret, Joubin (2007); p. 51.</ref> Over a total distance of {{convert|1185.22|km|mi|abbr=off}}, the fifteen stages totalled {{convert|328.54|km|miles|adj=pre|competitive|abbr=on}}, which was shorter than the FIA's regulatory minimum of {{convert|360|km|mi|abbr=on}} for Special Stages.<ref>WRC Sp. Regs. (2007); p. 2, <U+00A7>3.2.1.</ref> The drivers hoped that with the rally taking place on higher altitudes, wintery conditions and ''[[:fr:burle (vent)|burle]]'' (a freezing wind blowing from the north) would produce ice and snow on the ground, making for a more exciting event; however, except for some rain on Thursday evening it never came to fruition and the prevailing weather was clear and dry.<ref name="Yearbook 51" /><ref name="Pirelli 45">Holmes (2007); p. 45</ref> [[S<U+00E9>bastien Loeb]] was unhappy with the weekend's weather forecast. Following his reconnaissance run, he said, "With snow everywhere and walls on both sides of the road, like in the old days, some of these stages would have been brilliant. But because it's dry, in some places that makes it less interesting because than the roads further south with all their corners."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007'' at 6m 01s in.</ref> The service park in Valence was also much smaller than what had been used in Monaco, so there were no [[Production World Rally Championship]] or [[Junior Rally Championship]] categories, and  fewer entries of competitors.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Pirelli 46">Holmes (2007); p. 46.</ref> It was also badly located and poorly run,<ref name="Yearbook 51" /> and WRC's commercial director David Richards said that the service area was "like a [[car boot sale]]".<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" />

After being absent from the WRC for the 2006 season to spend thirteen months concentrating on preparing their new {{nowrap|[[Citro<U+00EB>n C4 WRC]]}} vehicle, the [[Citro<U+00EB>n Total World Rally Team]] returned in 2007 ready to d<U+00E9>but it in the Monte Carlo Rally. The [[Citro<U+00EB>n Xsara#Xsara WRC|Citro<U+00EB>n Xsara WRC]] had dominated the championship in recent years, and despite its age it was still incredibly reliable and was only replaced because the Xsara model was no longer in production.<ref>Holmes (2007); p. 157</ref> The C4's mechanical components, such as the engine, transmission, differentials and suspension were either very similar to, or came from, the Xsara,<ref name="Yearbook 28">Bourret, Joubin (2007); p. 28.</ref> but the [[wheelbase]] and [[chassis]] were longer by {{convert|253|mm|in|abbr=off}} and {{convert|107|mm|in|abbr=on}}, respectively, which meant that under WRC rules the C4 could be widened to {{convert|1800|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref>Holmes (2007); p. 157</ref> It was also higher than the Xsara, and the weight distribution had been fine-tuned, including raising and moving back the front seats (which had the negative effect of reducing the drivers' visibility), and attaching the [[wing mirrors]] to the midpoint along the front doors.<ref name="Yearbook 28" /><ref>''WRC Highlights 2007'' at 8m 53s in.</ref> The C4's test drivers reported that the car handled more stably.<ref>Holmes (2007); p. 157</ref>

Citro<U+00EB>n was confident the C4 would be successful yet concerned as to whether it would beat the {{nowrap|[[Ford Focus WRC|Ford Focus WRC 06]]}},<ref name="Rallycourse 68">Evans (2007); p. 68.</ref> which had won the [[List of World Rally Championship Constructors' champions|World Rally Championship for Manufacturers]] title in 2006 for the [[BP-Ford World Rally Team]]. The Focus, in addition had undergone its own developments during the winter break.<ref name="Yearbook 28" /> The tarmac testing of the C4 showed it to be faster than the outgoing Xsara,<ref name="Yearbook 28" /> but Loeb knew that that performance might not show itself in the race. "The car has been good in testing. But what about the rally?" he asked. "I don't know."<ref name="Rallycourse 68" /> [[Marcus Gr<U+00F6>nholm]], the Ford team's number 1 driver, was wary, however. "It's got thousands of k's on the clock. It was running when the Focus WRC 06 was still on the board."<ref name="Yearbook 28" /> Meanwhile, the [[Subaru World Rally Team]] were waiting for the {{nowrap|[[Subaru Impreza WRC|Subaru Impreza WRC 2007]]}} to be ready for the [[2007 Rally Mexico]] in March.<ref name="Pre-event" /> The team knew that the 2006 version, which had performed poorly the previous season, would be no match for the Focus or C4. Added to the fact that the cars were equipped with unfamiliar {{nowrap|[[BF Goodrich]]}} tyres after [[Pirelli]] decided not to supply any teams in 2007,<ref name="Yearbook 50">Bourret, Joubin (2007); p. 50.</ref> and they were hoping that [[Petter Solberg]] and [[Chris Atkinson]] could just earn some points from the race.<ref name="Pre-event" /><ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" />

Forty-nine crews registered to compete in the rally,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fia.com/sport/Championships/WRC/Entry_List/2007/Monte_Carlo/entry_list.html |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo 2007 Entry List |accessdate=13 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> Of the top-tier drivers entered, [[Jean-Marie Cuoq]] was the only WRC [[rookie]], and [[Chris Atkinson]], [[Henning Solberg]], and [[Matthew Wilson]] had driven at Monte Carlo only once before, all in [[2006 Monte Carlo Rally|2006]].<ref>Holmes (2007); pp. 142, 146.</ref> The starting order for [[Leg (rallying)|Leg]] 1 was "Priority 1" (P1) and P2 WRC drivers in [[2006 World Rally Championship season#Drivers' championship|the order of the final classification of the 2006 season]], followed by all other drivers as decided by the ACM.<ref>WRC Sp. Regs. (2007); p. 3, <U+00A7><U+00A7>3.5.2.1(a), 3.5.2.1(c).</ref> Loeb, the previous season's champion, set off first, followed by Gr<U+00F6>nholm, then [[Mikko Hirvonen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fia.com/sport/Championships/WRC/2006/Standings/driver.html |title=FIA WRC Drivers Championship Standings 2006 Season |date=2006 |accessdate=16 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> Loeb and Gr<U+00F6>nholm were the favourites to win; Loeb had won the Monte Carlo three times in a row between 2003 and 2005, and Gr<U+00F6>nholm had won in 2006.<ref>Holmes (2007); pp. 143<U+2013>144.</ref> Nevertheless, there were worries that Loeb would not be physically fit enough to win. Four months earlier he had broken his left shoulder in a mountain-biking accident, and there was a chance he might not even compete in the first part of the season.<ref name="Pirelli 44" /><ref>Evans (2007); p. 14.</ref> His physiotherapists and consultants told him that because of the operations he had had on his arm, he should definitely have sat out the Monte Carlo Rally. Loeb admitted that he was "really stressed" before the start, and wondered whether his arm would be okay.<ref>Evans (2007); p. 30.</ref> "It has been okay in testing but what about the long stages?" he asked. His answer: "I don't know."<ref name="Rallycourse 68" />

===Race===
Following a ten-year absence of nighttime-run stages,<ref name="Pirelli 44">Holmes (2007); p. 44.</ref> the first two Special Stages of the event were held on Thursday night.<ref name="Itinerary">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007121,00.html |title=2007 Monte Carlo Day 1 Timetable |accessdate=15 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070124013514/http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007121,00.html |year=2007 |archivedate=24 January 2007 }}</ref> They were the first night stages scheduled in the rally since 1997.<ref name="Pirelli 44" /> Throughout the day it had rained, and although it had stopped before the race began, the roads were still very wet and slippery.<ref name="Pre-event" /><ref name="Yearbook 48" /> In discussing the day's weather, Gr<U+00F6>nholm said that he expected the stages that night to be difficult, and added, "I hope this time we can take the right tyres, we were always a little bit on the wrong side [last year]&nbsp;<U+2013> it<U+2019>s not easy, but I hope we will manage to get it right this time."<ref name="Pre-event" /> Earlier in the day, the crews had driven a [[shakedown (testing)|shakedown]] stage in [[Mauves]]; however, due to a large number of fans and spectators along the route the shakedown was stopped early,<ref name="Pre-event" /> and some crews including Loeb and [[co-driver]] [[Daniel Elena]] were forced to carry out last-minute testing and necessary changes to their cars on the main roads back to Valence.<ref name="Yearbook 48">Bourret, Joubin (2007); p. 48.</ref> Though forty-nine crews registered in the rally, only forty-seven actually competed. Privateers [[Fran<U+00E7>ois Duval]] driving a {{nowrap|[[<U+0160>koda Fabia WRC]]}}, and [[Angelo Villa]] in a {{nowrap|[[Fiat Punto]]}} failed to start the event.<ref name="Yearbook 52-53" />

[[File:Loeb-rmc2007.jpeg|thumb|left|The [[Citro<U+00EB>n C4 WRC]], driven by [[S<U+00E9>bastien Loeb]] and [[Daniel Elena]], made its d<U+00E9>but during the Monte Carlo Rally. It was Loeb's first rally since breaking his arm four months prior.]]

The first stage of the rally started at {{nowrap|19:16 [[Central European Time]] ([[UTC+1]])}} on Thursday evening.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007121,00.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070613123916/http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007121,00.html |title=Timetable 2007 Monte Carlo Day  1 |archivedate=13 June 1007 |accessdate=20 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> The {{convert|28.52|km|mi|abbr=off}} winding route led the crews between ''{{lang|fr|[[Saint-Jean-en-Royans]]}}'' and ''{{lang|fr|[[Lachau|Col de Lachau]]}}''. Before taking to the tarmac, Chris Atkinson, in a {{nowrap|2006 Impreza WRC}} for the {{nowrap|Subaru WRT}}, admitted to never driving a tarmac stage at night before, but said it would be interesting to see how everybody performed.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 6m 05s in.</ref> His teammate Petter Solberg spoke of the challenges facing him: "[In the dark] everything gets a little bit more narrow and you always tend to be careful with how you turn in and keep the speed up in the corners, but obviously you have to listen to the pacenotes, that is absolutely crucial thing, 100%."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 5m 58s in.</ref> Loeb, who was familiar with driving on nighttime stages in the [[French Rally Championship]], said, "In the dark you have to drive like you can when you have only two passes on the recce, and then you also start with the fastest stage. I think there can be some big moments tonight."<ref name="Pre-event" /> Loeb and Elena took to the road first in their C4, and despite the limited visibility from both his ride position and the unlit roads, he set a pace time of {{nowrap|13m 58.7s}}. His teammate [[Dani Sordo]] and co-driver [[Marc Marti]] were able to keep up the pace, maxing out at {{convert|196|km/h|mph|abbr=off}} at one point along the route,<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 6m 55s in.</ref> and finished in {{nowrap|14m 07.2s}} for second place. Taking third place on the stage were the Ford crew of Gr<U+00F6>nholm and [[Timo Rautiainen (co-driver)|Timo Rautiainen]], who finished after {{nowrap|14 m 13.9s}}.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> On {{nowrap|Stage 2}}, a {{convert|17.88|km|mi|abbr=on}} run from ''{{lang|fr|La Cime du Mas}}'' to ''{{lang|fr|Col de Gaudissart}}'', Loeb held on to the lead, completing it in {{nowrap|9m 31.2s}}. Gr<U+00F6>nholm proved to be faster than Sordo on this stage, finishing with a time of {{nowrap|9m 45.5s}}, 1.1s faster than Sordo.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> At the end of Leg 1 and {{convert|46|km|mi|abbr=on}}, any worries about how well the new C4s would perform had been forgotten. They had beaten all the competition by a wide margin.<ref name="Yearbook 48" /> Loeb was almost {{nowrap|25 seconds}} ahead of his teammate, while Gr<U+00F6>nholm was {{nowrap|30 seconds}} adrift; and Petter Solberg, over {{nowrap|a minute}} behind the lead.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73">Evans (2007); pp. 72<U+2013>73.</ref><ref name="Yearbook 52-53">Bourret, Joubin (2007); pp. 52<U+2013>53.</ref>

There were six stages in {{nowrap|Leg 2}} on Friday, totalling {{convert|150.62|km|miles|adj=pre|competitive|abbr=on}}. {{nowrap|Stage 3}} was the first of these, starting at {{nowrap|08:19 CET}} in ''{{lang|fr|[[Saint-Pierreville]]}}''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007122,00.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070125094604/http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007122,00.html |title=Timetable 2007 Monte Carlo Day 2 |archivedate=25 January 1007 |accessdate=20 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> The route was {{convert|46.02|km|mi|abbr=on}} long and finished in ''{{lang|fr|[[Antraigues-sur-Volane|Antraigues]]}}''. The previous leg's provisional classification determined the starting order for Leg 2, whereby the {{nowrap|top 15}} {{nowrap|P1 and P2 drivers}} started in reverse order, followed by the remaining drivers in order of classification. [[Henning Solberg]] and [[Cato Menkelud]], driving a 2006-spec {{nowrap|Focus RS WRC}} for the {{nowrap|[[Stobart VK M-Sport Ford Rally Team]]}} were the first crew to take to the still-damp roads, and they set a time of {{nowrap|32m 52.9s}}. Their teammates, [[Matthew Wilson]] and [[Michael Orr]], completed the leg {{nowrap|a minute}} quicker, at {{nowrap|31m 42.5s}}.<ref name="Stage 3">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=3 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS3 St Pierreville 1 (46.02km) |accessdate=18 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> With no snow and ice on the roads, Sordo, who proved to be very quick on the tarmac surfaces last season,<ref name="Pre-event" /> was fastest on {{nowrap|Stage 3}}. He set a time of {{nowrap|29m 43.4s}}, a wide margin ahead of Loeb's and Gr<U+00F6>nholm's second- and third-placed times of {{nowrap|29m 59.6s}} and {{nowrap|30m 01.1s}}, respectively. Loeb was said to be "visibly shaken" from losing the stage to his less-experienced teammate.<ref name="Rallycourse 68" /> "I lost {{nowrap|16 seconds}}, my tyres were too hard," he said. "At the start they went cold and I wasn't in a good rhythm. Before we reached some dry parts I wasn't confident and I didn't want to take any big risks this morning."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 15m 02s in.</ref> Most drivers had problems with their tyre selection on {{nowrap|Stage 3}}, including Petter Solberg and Hirvonen. Petter was still trying to get used to the new BF Goodriches his car was outfitted with, but he found them too hard and said he could not find any feeling or grip with them.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 12m 00s in.</ref> Hirvonen, however, felt his tyre compound was too soft, and was unimpressed with his time.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 12m 42s in.</ref> Hirvonen completed the stage ninth, in {{nowrap|30m 41.5s}}, but Petter's time of {{nowrap|30m 50.0s}} was even worse, putting him in 12th position.<ref name="Stage 3" /> Petter's Subaru teammate Atkinson had no problems with his tyres, though, and he finished fourth with a time of {{nowrap|30m 03.5s}}. The [[Mitsubishi Lancer WRC]] crew of  [[Xavier Pons]] and [[Xavier Amigo]] had other troubles during this stage. The transmission failed and they had to retire from the rally.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 26m 22s in.</ref> Their teammates [[Toni Gardemeister]] and [[Jakke Honkanen]] set a good time on the stage when they finished in fifth place, as did OMV-Kronos's [[Manfred Stohl]] and [[Ilka Minor]] in sixth.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" />

At the end of {{nowrap|Stage 3}}, the podium positions were unchanged, but the time difference between Loeb and Sordo had decreased to seven seconds, although the gap between first place and fourth was over a minute.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> Petter Solberg had dropped out of contention for points, in ninth place overall, eighth being taken by [[Jan Kopeck<U+00FD>]] in a privately entered {{nowrap|[[<U+0160>koda Fabia WRC]]}}.<ref name="Stage 3" /> Before {{nowrap|Stages 4 and 5}} got underway, the crews had a chance to change their tyres to a set with a more suitable compound. A new WRC rule for 2007 allowed for Remote Service Zones to be set up away from the main Service Park at Rally HQ. For 15 minutes the cars could be refuelled, re-tyred, and have any necessary maintenance carried out, as long as the parts and tools to do so (except fuel and tyres) were already in the vehicle.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 15m 48s in.</ref> For Gr<U+00F6>nholm this was a major relief. On the previous stage his car had developed a issue with the hydraulic flappy-paddle gearchanges on his steering wheel,<ref name="Yearbook 49">Bourret, Joubin (2007); p. 49.</ref> which meant he had had to resort to shifting gears manually. The technicians were unsure why or how it had occurred and were hoping that their repairs would last until the car got back to Valence.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 16m 36s in.</ref> Loeb won an uneventful {{nowrap|Stage 4}}, but only by one-tenth of a second ahead of Sordo, and on {{nowrap|Stage 5}} Sordo was quicker than Loeb,<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> after Loeb stalled on the start-line and was unable to make up the lost seconds. At the midday break, Loeb was lamenting his lead over Sordo. "Now it's a big battle between the two C4s. The other cars for the moment are behind, so it's good news for the team. It would be easier if Dani were bit further behind but I have to deal wit that," he said. "I'll try to keep position this afternoon, but it's not easy. Dani is really fast. I only have a six-second lead."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 20m 10s in.</ref> Gr<U+00F6>nholm was also complaining. " The only good thing here is to win this rally, but to drive here; I don't like it."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 19m 47s in.</ref>

[[File:Gardemeister 2007.jpg|thumb|right|[[Toni Gardemeister]] and [[Jakke Honkanen]] finished the rally in 7th place driving a [[Mitsubishi Lancer WRC05]] for [[MMSP Ltd]], earning him 2 points in the [[List of World Rally Championship Drivers' champions|World Rally Championship for Drivers]].]]

{{nowrap|Stage 6}} was a rerun of the ''{{lang|fr|[[Saint-Pierreville]]}}&nbsp;<U+2013> {{lang|fr|[[Antraigues-sur-Volane|Antraigues]]}}'' stage from the morning. The roads had dried out by the afternoon, but that did not stop some crews from having accidents along the route. Stohl spun out as he went through a corner, and crashed the front of his car into the stone wall of a house. He continued on, but the front bumper was damaged and hanging loose. "We lost the front brakes completely," Stohl explained. "Absolutely no brakes. I was lucky to finish because I was nearly off sometimes."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 21m 32s in.</ref> Despite his difficulties, he managed to finish the stage in {{nowrap|29m 37.6s}} which put him in {{nowrap|10th position}} for the stage, and {{nowrap|8th overall}}.<ref name="Stage 6">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=6 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS6 St Pierreville 2 (46.02km) |accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> The dry roads meant that all the drivers were able to complete the stage faster than they had been in the morning.<ref name="Stage 3" /><ref name="Stage 6" /> At just {{convert|5|km|mi|abbr=on}} Loeb was already much faster than his time during {{nowrap|Stage 3}},<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 24m 22s in.</ref> but on a narrow stretch of the route towards the {{lang|fr|Col de la Fayolle}} he did not brake into a corner at the right time and skidded and collided with a fence.<ref name="Yearbook 49" /> He was able to carry on driving, but co-driver Elena's door and sill were damaged.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 23m 55s in.</ref> Despite the accident, he won the stage, and increased the overall gap between himself and Sordo from {{nowrap|6.5 seconds}} to nearly {{nowrap|24 seconds}}. A repeat run of {{nowrap|Stages 4 and 5}} closed the day. Sordo won {{nowrap|Stage 8}} and Loeb took {{nowrap|Stage 9}}.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> But by the end of the Leg and {{convert|550.02|km|mi|abbr=on}} of driving, Loeb's arm and shoulder were in great pain and his osteopath worked through the night to try to address the problems.<ref name="Yearbook 48" />

{{nowrap|Leg 3}} began early Saturday morning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007123,00.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070126202906/http://www.wrc.com/page/Timetable/0,,10111~2007123,00.html |title=Timetable 2007 Monte Carlo Day 3 |archivedate=26 January 1007 |accessdate=20 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> Following Friday's stages, Loeb was {{nowrap|25 seconds}} ahead of Sordo, and {{nowrap|1m 15s}} in front of Gr<U+00F6>nholm. {{nowrap|Stage 9}} was the first of the day, a {{convert|19.67|km|mi|abbr=on}} route between {{lang|fr|[[Labatie-d'Andaure]]}} and {{lang|fr|[[Lalouvesc]]}} held in darkness.  Loeb, Sordo, and Gr<U+00F6>nholm once again finished first, second and third.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> Atkinson suffered a setback when he crashed his car and stalled it.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 28m 39s in.</ref> It cost him a few seconds and he finished the stage ninth, behind Hirvonen, [[Jean-Marie Cuoq]], Gardemeister and Kopeck<U+00FD>, but he retained his fourth place standing in the event's classifications.<ref name="Stage 9">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=9 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS9 Labatie D'Andaure 1 (19.67km) |accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> The surprise result of Stage 10 was Atkinson's. He broke Loeb's and Sordo's run and was the first fastest non-Citro<U+00EB>n driver of the rally, and set a time of {{nowrap|12m 42s}}.<ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /><ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" />

Henning Solberg, meanwhile, went off the road and into a ditch as he entered a one of the corners on the stage,<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 41m 17s in.</ref> and his brother Petter had a similar problem in the same corner, but his quick reactions were able to control the car so he just drove into the scrub and got back on track. Henning finished in seventeenth place,<ref name="Stage 10">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=10 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS10 St Bonnet 1 (25.93km) |accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> and Petter finished joint-fifth with Cuoq on {{nowrap|12m 50.4s}}.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /> Loeb ran his slowest time on this stage after he reduced speed and his tyres went cold. "I was a bit faster than Dani [Sordo] on the start of the stage, and then I saw my splits [times between checkpoints] and then I tried to slow down," he explained. "We had hard tyres and when you slow down the tyres [cool down] and then you lose the grip more and more, and at the end it was really tricky and I had cold tyres, so I just tried to slow down. The end [of the stage] was really tricky so I didn't want to take any risks."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 36m 33s in.</ref> {{nowrap|Stage 11}} was won by Hirvonen with a time of {{nowrap|11m 46.9s}}. Loeb was 1.2s slower and finished second. Atkinson lost all the time he made up in {{nowrap|Stage 10}} by finishing in eighth place, {{nowrap|11.4 seconds}} slower than Hirvonen. This reduced the gap between the two in the overall classifications to just {{nowrap|8.9 seconds}}. Sordo, meanwhile, had his worst stage and finished in {{nowrap|10th position}}.<ref name="Stage 11">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=11 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS11 Lamastre 1 (18.76km) |accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref>

[[File:2007 Monte Carlo Rally SS15 map.svg|thumb|left|Special Stage 15 was the only stage of the Monte Carlo Rally to be held in Monte Carlo. It used the lower part of the [[Circuit de Monaco]], normally reserved for the [[Monaco Grand Prix]].]]

After the midday service, the next three stages were reruns of the morning's. Hirvonen won {{nowrap|Stage 12}} and Atkinson had another slow run, which resulted in Hirvonen taking fourth place in the provisional classification by four-tenths of a second.<ref name="Stage 12">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=12 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS12 Labatie D'Andaure 2 (19.67km) |accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> On {{nowrap|Stage 13}}, Atkinson retook his fourth-placed position after winning the stage with a time of {{nowrap|12m 32.4w}}, and beating Hirvonen by {{nowrap|7.6 seconds}}.<ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /><ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /> "Considering how ordinary I drove in the first one, I had to pull my finger out!" said Atkinson. He regained his fourth place position just {{nowrap|7.2 seconds}} ahead of Hirvonen. Loeb was slow again, 6.7 seconds slower than his teammate, Sordo, which cut the time between them to {{nowrap|23.2 seconds}}.<ref name="Stage 13">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=13 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS13 St Bonnet 2 (25.93km)|accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> "No problem, the car is going very well," said Loeb. "One stage more to go and hopefully its okay."

Stage 14 was the last in the mountains of Ardeche, before travelling to Monte Carlo for the Super Special Stage. For most drivers it was going to be the last time to gain higher positions in the classifications.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 41m 39s in.</ref> Loeb, although slow again, extended his lead in the standings to {{nowrap|31.1 seconds}}, by finishing in fourth position with a time of {{nowrap|11m 47.7s}}.<ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /><ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /> Sordo also had another bad stage. He finished the stage ninth-fastest after {{nowrap|11m 55.6s}} on the road.<ref name="Stage 14">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=14 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS14 Lamastre 2 (18.76km)|accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref> For Hirvonen, it was the last good chance to retake fourth position from Atkinson, which he did when he won the stage by setting the pace time of {{nowrap|11m 30.5s}}. Atkinson ran {{nowrap|8 seconds}} slower and finished second. It was also [[Jari-Matti Latvala]]'s last chance to earn a points position. Kopeck<U+00FD> had been in eighth position and set to score one point since the middle of the second Leg, but Latvala was just {{nowrap|5.4 seconds}} behind him going into this stage.<ref name="Stage 13" /> But Latvala pushed too hard and when he drove over some loose gravel he lost control and slid the car into the end of a stone wall. The impact caused damage to the car's [[roll cage]] which forced him to retire from the rally and end his attempt to earn any points.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 41m 51s in.</ref>

The final stage of the rally took place on Sunday morning. After conducting the entire race in France the organisers only paid lip service to the principality by holding a Super Special Stage there.<ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /><ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /> It involved two laps of part of the [[Circuit de Monaco]] for a total distance of {{convert|2.8|km|mi|abbr=on}}, with two cars on the road at the same time but starting at two different points along the track so that they did not interfere with each other.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 45m 00s in.</ref> Because the Service Park was in Valence, repairs, adjustments, refuelling and tyre changes were carried out on Saturday night ahead of the drive down to the coast. The decision about which tyres to fit on the cars was taken out of the teams' hands. ACM ordered that all the cars would drive on the snow tyres that the teams had been allocated, but had not been used because of the dry weather, a decision that was described as "absurd"<ref name="Pirelli 45" /> because the cars ended up [[drifting (motorsport)|drifting]] through the corners.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 45m 05s in.</ref> Loeb's, Sordo's and Gr<U+00F6>nholm's lead times so far ahead of anyone else's, so the interest in Stage 15 was on Hirvonen and Atkinson. Only eight-tenths of a second made the difference between a fourth place position and five points, and fifth-placed position and four points. Hirvonen, who was in fourth place, completed the stage in {{nowrap|1m 50.9s}}, and admitted, "[I made] a few small mistakes, and that can be it. Nothing more I can do. We'll see how Chris drives and hope for the best.". Atkinson drove opposite Gr<U+00F6>nholm on the stage, with Hirvonen watching from the sidelines.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 46m 52s in.</ref> To beat Hirvonen, he had to complete the stage in {{nowrap|1m 50.0s}}. He was one-tenth of a second quicker than that, which won him the stage and fourth place in the rally.<ref name="Stage 15">{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/stage-times/?category=wrc&stageno=15 |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Stage Times&nbsp;<U+2013> SS15 Monaco (2.79km)|accessdate=19 April 2012 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref>

===Post-race===
Loeb was delighted with his win at Monte Carlo, saying, "It's a victory in Monte Carlo so that's a great moment. I like to start the season like this, with ten points. That's really important for me, the feeling is good. The car is really, really fast and my arm is much better, so everything is perfect for the moment."<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 49m 50s in.</ref> [[Guy Fr<U+00E9>quelin]], the Team Principal at  Citro<U+00EB>n Total was also pleased with Leob's and Sordo's results. He said afterwards,
{{quote|It's a really a fantastic start for Citro<U+00EB>n, for the team, for the crews. It's really fantastic, and for the chief, for sure! This is the result of a huge team effort. To do this in the first event, every member of the Citro<U+00EB>n Sport team had to come together in a common goal. I think it's a wonderful reward for our pus to come back to the World Championship. It's not often that a car making its competition d<U+00E9>but produces results like these: nine fastest times, eight on them 1<U+2013>2s. And there aren't many models that have dominated and scored a 1<U+2013>2 finish in their first race, either. The Citro<U+00EB>n C4 WRC has really made its presence felt on its international d<U+00E9>but.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 50m 27s in.</ref><ref name="Yearbook 49" />}}

The last time a car had finished in first and second-place in its d<U+00E9>but rally was 20 years ago in the [[1987 Monte Carlo Rally]], when [[Miki Biasion]] and [[Juha Kankkunen]] came first and second in all-new [[Lancia Delta#HF 4WD|Lancia Delta HF 4WD]]s. The Delta HF 4<U+00D7>4 also won two-thirds of all the stages of that 1987 rally, just like the C4 did this time around. Lancia also won both the [[Group A#Rallying|Group A]] and [[Group N#Rally racing|Group N]] categories in the race, while Citro<U+00EB>n won the 4-wheel drive [[World Rally Car|WRC]] category and came first in the 2-wheel drive [[Super 1600]] category.<ref name="Pirelli 45" />

{{quote box|"For me this victory was one of the best, because we had a lot of questions before the start. I was a bit stressed on Thursday; it was a lot we didn<U+2019>t know. The feeling was good, but in the race you need to be able to improvise and be confident in the car and we didn<U+2019>t know. Also my arm, it was my first race in four months, some new stages, rain and in the night&nbsp;<U+2013> it was a lot of new things. For us it<U+2019>s good news to see the C4 was competitive and to fight for the victory and to win."|width=50%|source=[[S<U+00E9>bastien Loeb]], commenting on the weekend in the post-race press conference.<ref name="Post-race">{{cite press |url=http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Information/WRC/Press_Conferences/2007/mon_conf2.html |title=Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo Post-event Press Conference |accessdate=20 April 2012 |date=21 January 2007 |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref>}}

Gr<U+00F6>nholm was disappointed with his race, admitting that he thought he might be able to beat Sordo, if not Loeb. But after having gearbox and tyre problems on {{nowrap|Leg 2}}, he settled into third place and stayed in that position to the rally's conclusion. "We got it wrong on the tyre choice, which we had to have approved by the FIA early in the week," he explained. "We thought it would rain. Harder tyres would have made life easier for us."<ref name="Yearbook 49" /> BP-Ford was also unhappy. Christian Loriaux, the team's Technical Director said, "Having Marcus finish behind Sordo is disappointing. Being behind Loeb is easier to understand, because I didn't expect the C4 to be any slower than the Xsara, and that car had a performance edge over us last year."<ref name="Yearbook 50" /> Petter Solberg also had issues with his tyres throughout the rally. After Subaru switched to {{nowrap|BF Goodrich}}es from Pirelli following the 2006 season, and with the shortest break between seasons the WRC had seen, the crews had not had enough time to test the new compounds. The Subarus had had their problems with the Pirellis, too. To protect them from breaking up too quickly the drivers had learned how to look after them, but driving that way on the new brand meant that he could not get the BFs up to temperature and ended up running slower.<ref name="Yearbook 50" /> He finished the rally in sixth place.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /><ref name="Pirelli 47" /> His teammate Atkinson did not have that problem though, and after fighting with Hirvonen in the final half of the rally, finished in fourth place. "It's been a massive battle, and so much fun to be in a battle with these guys again," he said after being congratulated by Hirvonen.<ref>''WRC Highlights 2007''; at 48m 18s in.</ref> Two drivers in non-manufacturer cars, Gardemeister and Kopeck<U+00FD>, finished in seventh and eighth place to receive drivers points.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /><ref name="Pirelli 47" />

As a consequence of the final positions, Loeb started the season leading in the [[List of World Rally Championship Drivers' champions|World Rally Championship for Drivers]] with ten points. Sordo was second with eight points, Gr<U+00F6>nholm was in third position with six points. In the [[List of World Rally Championship Constructors' champions|World Rally Championship for Manufacturers]], Stobart Ford had one point from Henning Solberg's fourteenth-placed position (although Wilson finished the rally quicker, he was not nominated to earn points for the manufacturer). Stohl earned OMV-Kronos Citro<U+00EB>n two points. Subaru were in third place with eight points, BP-Ford were two points clear of Subaru in second place, and Citro<U+00EB>n Total WRT was first, with eighteen points <U+2013> ten from Loeb's win and eight from Sordo.<ref name="Rallycourse 72-73" /><ref name="Yearbook 52-53" /><ref name="Pirelli 47" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrc.com/results/2007/rallye-automobile-monte-carlo/final-results/ |title=Rallye Automobile Monte Carlo&nbsp;<U+2013> Final Results |publisher={{lang|fr|[[F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]}} }}</ref>

